It's everywhere. His
body's not filtering it.

485
00:26:47,005 --> 00:26:48,439
His kidneys are failing.

486
00:26:53,011 --> 00:26:54,707
I told you to nuke his thyroid.

487
00:26:54,780 --> 00:26:57,773
It's a good thing we didn't. Kidney
failure means it wasn't Graves'.

488
00:26:57,883 --> 00:27:01,911
So, your test screwed me
and our patient's kidneys.

489
00:27:02,020 --> 00:27:03,431
You practically
poisoned him with iodine.

490
00:27:03,455 --> 00:27:06,448
Which he could have handled
easily if his kidneys were healthy.

491
00:27:06,558 --> 00:27:09,460
All we did was reveal a new
symptom. Usually you're all for that.

492
00:27:09,561 --> 00:27:11,928
It must be the rancid tinge
of betrayal that's put me off.

493
00:27:11,997 --> 00:27:13,124
You were wrong.

494
00:27:13,198 --> 00:27:14,894
So, tell me to my face.

495
00:27:15,334 --> 00:27:18,668
You've never hesitated before.
The board's turning you into a coward.

496
00:27:18,770 --> 00:27:20,636
I did it because it was
the right thing to do.

497
00:27:20,706 --> 00:27:22,004
You did it to pass
an inspection.

498
00:27:22,107 --> 00:27:23,735
Does it matter?

499
00:27:24,309 --> 00:27:27,643
Kidney failure on top of the other
symptoms points to an autoimmune condition,

500
00:27:27,746 --> 00:27:30,944
which means that any of his
other organs could be next.

501
00:27:31,416 --> 00:27:35,820
We've already started dialysis. We
need to run ANA's for autoimmune.

502
00:27:36,788 --> 00:27:40,281
You're right. You and the
team go measure the ceilings.

503
00:27:41,193 --> 00:27:42,252
Excuse me?

504
00:27:42,327 --> 00:27:44,193
Accreditation Board
guidelines state that

505
00:27:44,296 --> 00:27:47,198
no object can be less than
18 inches from the ceiling.

506
00:27:47,299 --> 00:27:48,476
Make sure we're in compliance.

507
00:27:48,500 --> 00:27:50,445
There's nothing in our
office that would be less...

508
00:27:50,469 --> 00:27:52,961
I don't mean us. I
mean the whole hospital.

509
00:28:00,312 --> 00:28:02,645
Let's see how this baby handles.

510
00:28:16,228 --> 00:28:17,491
What?

511
00:28:17,563 --> 00:28:19,031
You bought the firm mattress.

512
00:28:20,832 --> 00:28:22,391
I thought that's the
one you wanted.

513
00:28:22,467 --> 00:28:23,867
It was.

514
00:28:24,670 --> 00:28:26,104
Why would you do that?

515
00:28:26,171 --> 00:28:27,195
Because...

516
00:28:29,374 --> 00:28:31,309
Is this a trick question?

517
00:28:31,376 --> 00:28:32,605
I left it up to you.

518
00:28:33,512 --> 00:28:35,913
You were supposed to
get the one you wanted.

519
00:28:37,683 --> 00:28:39,777
I got the one you wanted
because I love you.

520
00:28:39,885 --> 00:28:40,944
No.

521
00:28:45,357 --> 00:28:48,088
You did it because
that's what you do.

522
00:28:48,627 --> 00:28:50,271
With all your ex-wives, you
did whatever they wanted

523
00:28:50,295 --> 00:28:53,197
because it was easier, and
you ended up resenting them.

524
00:28:54,299 --> 00:28:56,200
Don't you dare do that to me.

525
00:28:57,736 --> 00:28:59,364
What, take care of you?

526
00:29:00,606 --> 00:29:02,234
Have you met me?

527
00:29:02,774 --> 00:29:04,640
I can take care of me.

528
00:29:05,277 --> 00:29:07,303
I need you to take care of you.

529
00:29:09,214 --> 00:29:10,546
I have work to do.

530
00:29:18,323 --> 00:29:20,087
You made it to page eight.

531
00:29:21,727 --> 00:29:24,561
"Mysterious Hospital
Visit for Soap Doc."

532
00:29:25,297 --> 00:29:28,062
Wow, I'll be sure to
send my mom a copy.

533
00:29:31,169 --> 00:29:34,003
They told me I have
an autoimmune disease,

534
00:29:34,106 --> 00:29:36,769
like Lupus or Sarcoidosis.

535
00:29:38,277 --> 00:29:40,678
That's what we're
here to find out.

536
00:29:44,116 --> 00:29:46,847
You really as good as
everyone seems to think you are?

537
00:29:46,952 --> 00:29:51,048
Are you really as miserable as
everyone seems to think you are?

538
00:29:51,156 --> 00:29:55,025
I just want to do
something that matters.

539
00:29:57,195 --> 00:29:58,857
Nothing matters.

540
00:29:58,964 --> 00:30:04,130
We're all just cockroaches,
wildebeests dying on the riverbank.

541
00:30:05,570 --> 00:30:07,505
Nothing we do has
any lasting meaning.

542
00:30:07,572 --> 00:30:09,666
And you think I'm miserable?

543
00:30:09,741 --> 00:30:12,836
If you're unhappy on
the plane, jump out of it.

544
00:30:13,145 --> 00:30:14,511
I want to,

545
00:30:16,748 --> 00:30:17,875
but I can't.

546
00:30:19,551 --> 00:30:23,215
That's the problem with
metaphors. They need interpretation.

547
00:30:23,755 --> 00:30:26,725
Jumping out of
the plane is stupid.

548
00:30:27,259 --> 00:30:29,160
But what if I'm not in a plane?

549
00:30:31,029 --> 00:30:33,589
What if I'm just in a
place I don't want to be?

550
00:30:36,034 --> 00:30:37,832
That's the other
problem with metaphors.

551
00:30:37,903 --> 00:30:40,202
Yes, what if you're actually
in an ice cream truck,

552
00:30:40,272 --> 00:30:42,673
and outside are candy
and flowers and virgins?

553
00:30:42,741 --> 00:30:46,940
You're on a plane.
We're all on planes.

554
00:30:48,013 --> 00:30:52,576
Life is dangerous and complicated,
and it's a long way down.

555
00:30:54,786 --> 00:30:56,687
So, you're afraid to change?

556
00:30:58,490 --> 00:31:00,391
No, you're afraid to change.

557
00:31:01,093 --> 00:31:05,326
You'd rather imagine that you
can escape, instead of actually try,

558
00:31:06,598 --> 00:31:09,432
because if you fail,
you've got nothing.

559
00:31:10,469 --> 00:31:13,633
So, you'll give up the
chance at something real,

560
00:31:13,739 --> 00:31:15,571
so you that can hold on to hope.

561
00:31:16,808 --> 00:31:19,835
Thing is, hope is for sissies.

562
00:31:23,482 --> 00:31:26,509
When I get out of here, I'm
not going to be afraid anymore.

563
00:31:28,353 --> 00:31:31,187
I mean, how many guys
get a second chance?

564
00:31:31,289 --> 00:31:36,193
Too many. Half the people I save
don't deserve a second chance.

565
00:31:36,294 --> 00:31:39,594
Now that I've got mine,
I'm going to set things right.

566
00:31:41,366 --> 00:31:45,667
I'm going to start by being a better
father to you and to your sister.

567
00:31:46,972 --> 00:31:49,305
And to your other sister.
And to your other sister.

568
00:31:50,542 --> 00:31:53,341
You realize you're reciting
lines from last season?

569
00:31:53,445 --> 00:31:56,279
We're going to do all
the things I promised.

570
00:31:57,682 --> 00:31:59,981
Just help me get
out of this bed.

571
00:32:06,291 --> 00:32:09,819
Cooling blankets in here.
This guy's brain is about to boil.

572
00:32:11,997 --> 00:32:14,398
Do you know where you
are? What's your name?

573
00:32:14,766 --> 00:32:16,496
Dr. Brock Sterling.

574
00:32:22,908 --> 00:32:26,242
Fever rules out autoimmune. He's
septic. He's got a massive infection.

575
00:32:26,311 --> 00:32:28,055
We've got him on
broad-spectrum antibiotics,

576
00:32:28,079 --> 00:32:30,571
but he's slipped from
delirium into a coma.

577
00:32:30,649 --> 00:32:34,142
Good news is last time Brock was
in a coma, he fathered two children.

578
00:32:34,252 --> 00:32:37,654
We need to identify the infection and
get him on more targeted meds fast.

579
00:32:37,756 --> 00:32:40,037
What about pneumococcus?
Causes heart problems and sepsis.

580
00:32:40,125 --> 00:32:42,804
But not the neuropathies in his foot
and eyes. What about tetanus? It fits.

581
00:32:42,828 --> 00:32:45,457
He got a tetanus booster
last year. Lyme disease?

582
00:32:45,530 --> 00:32:46,774
He would have
been sore all over.

583
00:32:46,798 --> 00:32:48,476
There's a thousand infections
that could have caused this.

584
00:32:48,500 --> 00:32:51,937
We can start testing, but he'll
be dead before the cultures grow.

585
00:32:52,003 --> 00:32:56,464
Unless it's a fungus. We could
see that under a microscope.

586
00:32:56,541 --> 00:33:00,137
Test for fungi, parasites,
all creatures great and small.

587
00:33:00,712 --> 00:33:01,839
Where are you going?

588
00:33:01,913 --> 00:33:03,905
To lie down. I need to think.

589
00:33:08,053 --> 00:33:12,684
Could be rat bite fever,
but his glands aren't swollen.

590
00:33:15,360 --> 00:33:17,488
Which one are you going to get?

591
00:33:17,829 --> 00:33:19,798
She told me to
get the one I want.

592
00:33:19,865 --> 00:33:20,924
So get it.

593
00:33:22,334 --> 00:33:26,897
Listeria explains the sepsis,
possibly also the heart problem.

594
00:33:27,005 --> 00:33:28,564
But not the numbness.

595
00:33:29,341 --> 00:33:33,278
If the listeria caused encephalomyelitis,
which then caused the numbness...

596
00:33:34,679 --> 00:33:36,409
I want a waterbed.

597
00:33:42,420 --> 00:33:43,752
Wow.

598
00:33:43,855 --> 00:33:48,020
I've always wanted one. I
know it's ridiculous, it's just

599
00:33:48,093 --> 00:33:51,860
there's something nice about the
thought of being rocked to sleep in water.

600
00:33:55,200 --> 00:33:58,466
No mocking? No Freudian
analysis of how the waterbed

601
00:33:58,570 --> 00:34:01,768
is really a great big
vagina I want to crawl into?

602
00:34:02,073 --> 00:34:04,702
I'm ignoring you because
you make me sad.

603
00:34:05,377 --> 00:34:08,074
He's on ampicillin, which
means if it was listeria,

604
00:34:08,146 --> 00:34:09,580
he would've shown
some improvement.

605
00:34:09,648 --> 00:34:13,949
No, it's a whole thing. You need
special sheets and insurance and...

606
00:34:14,052 --> 00:34:17,580
Who cares? You wanted
one your whole life.

607
00:34:17,656 --> 00:34:20,820
You're a grown-up. You
can afford it. Stores sell them.

608
00:34:20,926 --> 00:34:23,452
Most adults don't go through
life like you do, House,

609
00:34:23,528 --> 00:34:25,360
indulging our every whim.

610
00:34:25,697 --> 00:34:27,666
Then you don't
deserve to be happy.

611
00:34:27,766 --> 00:34:29,598
And yet I am. You?

612
00:34:36,875 --> 00:34:38,810
Amber will think it's stupid.

613
00:34:42,113 --> 00:34:43,547
It is stupid.

614
00:34:48,720 --> 00:34:50,655
Live the dream, Wilson.

615
00:34:54,125 --> 00:34:58,028
It's not an infection.
It's an allergy.

616
00:34:58,129 --> 00:35:00,223
That's why it's not
responding to antibiotics.

617
00:35:00,332 --> 00:35:01,664
This isn't a soap opera, House.

618
00:35:01,733 --> 00:35:04,828
People don't just wake up from
comas the second you give them drugs.

619
00:35:04,903 --> 00:35:07,964
Especially if we give them the
wrong drugs. What do the tests say?

620
00:35:08,039 --> 00:35:10,484
It was negative for fungus and
parasites, but that doesn't mean...

621
00:35:10,508 --> 00:35:13,654
The more infections we rule out, the more
likely it is that it's not an infection.

622
00:35:13,678 --> 00:35:16,739
He has no history of allergies
or asthma. Most importantly,

623
00:35:16,848 --> 00:35:19,545
none of his symptoms remotely
resemble an allergic reaction.

624
00:35:19,651 --> 00:35:22,177
Allergens could trigger
an allergic vasculitis.

625
00:35:22,253 --> 00:35:23,464
That would explain the symptoms.

626
00:35:23,488 --> 00:35:24,751
One in a million times.

627
00:35:24,856 --> 00:35:26,757
Septic infection always
explains his symptoms.

628
00:35:26,858 --> 00:35:29,692
But an infection is never
resistant to every antibiotic.

629
00:35:29,761 --> 00:35:31,201
No, an infection
is rarely resistant.

630
00:35:31,329 --> 00:35:36,529
And allergy never responds to antibiotics.
"Never" beats "rarely." QED, I win.

631
00:35:36,601 --> 00:35:38,502
There were chrysanthemums
in his dressing room.

632
00:35:38,570 --> 00:35:40,937
My God, why didn't you say
he'd been exposed to plant life?

633
00:35:41,039 --> 00:35:45,033
Chrysanthemums contain pyrethrin.
It's a neurotoxin and a known allergen.

634
00:35:45,110 --> 00:35:48,547
He has an infection. If we
give him steroids, we'll kill him.

635
00:35:48,613 --> 00:35:51,158
He has an allergy. If we don't
give him steroids, we'll kill him.

636
00:35:51,182 --> 00:35:52,182
Not as fast.

637
00:35:52,250 --> 00:35:53,445
Fast enough.

638
00:35:53,551 --> 00:35:55,663
You don't have time for the rest of
the tests. We have to do something.

639
00:35:55,687 --> 00:35:58,122
And what we're doing
right now isn't working.

640
00:36:01,226 --> 00:36:03,821
Hundred milligrams
methylprednisolone.

641
00:36:03,928 --> 00:36:05,453
Patients' names?

642
00:36:05,530 --> 00:36:07,089
It's one patient.

643
00:36:07,165 --> 00:36:10,966
You want to give one patient 100
milligrams? That'll jump-start a car.

644
00:36:11,069 --> 00:36:14,096
Perfect, my patient's
a '69 Ford Coma.

645
00:36:14,172 --> 00:36:16,641
Anything over 50 milligrams, I
need a sign-off from Dr. Cuddy.

646
00:36:16,741 --> 00:36:18,801
It's protocol, and
the inspector's here.

647
00:36:18,910 --> 00:36:22,403
I am 99% certain
that she'll consent.

648
00:36:22,480 --> 00:36:25,143
But for the sake of the
1%, why don't I just...

649
00:36:25,517 --> 00:36:27,281
You're not allowed back here.

650
00:36:27,352 --> 00:36:29,753
Well, tell the inspector
he can put it on my tab.

651
00:36:35,360 --> 00:36:37,022
I didn't mean now.

652
00:36:47,238 --> 00:36:51,073
100 milligrams of
methylprednisolone is an overdose.

653
00:36:51,176 --> 00:36:52,906
We were wrong
about the infection.

654
00:36:53,011 --> 00:36:55,173
He's suffering from a
severe allergic reaction.

655
00:36:55,246 --> 00:36:57,738
The team hasn't finished
the test for allergy.

656
00:36:57,849 --> 00:36:58,849
His symptoms don't...

657
00:36:58,917 --> 00:37:00,545
In rare cases...

658
00:37:01,386 --> 00:37:03,514
Trust me, at the end of
this conversation, I'm right.

659
00:37:03,588 --> 00:37:06,080
Then confirm it.
Get a blood test.

660
00:37:06,191 --> 00:37:09,628
What is it about this
severe and deepening coma

661
00:37:09,728 --> 00:37:11,338
that makes you think
we've got time for protocol?

662
00:37:11,362 --> 00:37:13,140
Protocol has saved your
patient from having his

663
00:37:13,164 --> 00:37:15,463
thyroid destroyed
and his blood drained.

664
00:37:16,234 --> 00:37:21,104
If you think I'm wrong, tell me I'm
wrong. Don't talk about protocol.

665
00:37:24,375 --> 00:37:28,039
My job's on the line.
Your job is on the line.

666
00:37:30,882 --> 00:37:32,646
Okay, here's what you do.

667
00:37:33,451 --> 00:37:36,910
You wait three minutes,
then you call security.

668
00:37:36,988 --> 00:37:40,425
By the time they get in here
to lock me up, I'll be done.

669
00:37:40,492 --> 00:37:43,553
He gets to live. Your
ass gets to be covered.

670
00:37:49,167 --> 00:37:54,470
If he dies, let me know,
so I can pack my things.

671
00:38:45,056 --> 00:38:49,460
Tests are negative. Patient's
negative for all floral allergies.

672
00:38:52,197 --> 00:38:55,861
I'm going to restart
the antibiotics.

673
00:38:58,536 --> 00:39:00,368
If he's still alive.

674
00:39:09,881 --> 00:39:12,248
Ampicillin, two grams, IV.

675
00:39:13,751 --> 00:39:17,347
Why? The steroids
worked. House was right.

676
00:39:17,422 --> 00:39:18,446
The test was negative.

677
00:39:18,523 --> 00:39:19,821
He was still right.

678
00:39:21,259 --> 00:39:22,659
It was an allergy.

679
00:39:22,727 --> 00:39:24,093
To what?

680
00:39:25,864 --> 00:39:27,230
Thank you.

681
00:39:31,369 --> 00:39:32,769
I was wrong.

682
00:39:34,539 --> 00:39:36,531
You should have stopped me.

683
00:39:40,912 --> 00:39:43,939
Heard about House's
patient. Bold move.

684
00:39:45,383 --> 00:39:47,545
And you backed him.

685
00:39:47,619 --> 00:39:48,712
He was right.

686
00:39:49,520 --> 00:39:52,183
He wasn't even in the
same neighborhood as right.

687
00:39:52,257 --> 00:39:53,281
The patient's alive.

688
00:39:53,391 --> 00:39:57,226
Okay, the rules exist
because 95% of the time,

689
00:39:57,295 --> 00:39:59,730
for 95% of people,
they're the right thing to do.

690
00:39:59,797 --> 00:40:01,766
And the other 5%?

691
00:40:01,833 --> 00:40:03,529
Have to live by the same rules.

692
00:40:04,202 --> 00:40:07,070
Because everybody
thinks they're in that 5%.

693
00:40:09,407 --> 00:40:10,431
Okay.

694
00:40:12,076 --> 00:40:13,738
I noticed that Dr. Chase...

695
00:40:34,999 --> 00:40:37,161
What are you doing out here?

696
00:40:38,937 --> 00:40:41,099
I can't sleep. I
hate the waterbed.

697
00:40:46,210 --> 00:40:48,270
I actually kind of like it.

698
00:40:48,346 --> 00:40:50,178
No, it's awful.

699
00:40:51,849 --> 00:40:53,977
We're returning it tomorrow.

700
00:40:55,386 --> 00:40:56,513
Okay.

701
00:41:07,732 --> 00:41:09,530
I'm glad you got it, though.

702
00:41:10,902 --> 00:41:12,131
Me, too.

703
00:41:15,239 --> 00:41:17,504
I hope they'll take it back.

704
00:41:19,711 --> 00:41:21,145
They will.

705
00:41:27,752 --> 00:41:30,347
<i>You promised me
you'd stop drinking.</i>

706
00:41:31,889 --> 00:41:36,350
<i>Of course I'm drunk, Anna. They told
me you'd never wake up from that coma.</i>

707
00:41:36,427 --> 00:41:39,556
<i>But how could you get
engaged to my sister?</i>

708
00:41:44,002 --> 00:41:45,732
<i>We fell in love.</i>

709
00:41:46,738 --> 00:41:49,765
<i>What do you want from
me, Anna? I'm just a man.</i>

710
00:41:50,575 --> 00:41:52,203
<i>And I'm just a woman.</i>

711
00:41:52,276 --> 00:41:54,541
<i>And as thrilled as I am
about The Lady Slipper being</i>

712
00:41:54,612 --> 00:41:57,673
<i>the best nightclub Port
Lawrence has ever seen...</i>

713
00:42:14,799 --> 00:42:16,392
Hello. <i>HOUSE: Don't hang up.</i>

714
00:42:17,802 --> 00:42:19,464
What was the verdict?

715
00:42:19,537 --> 00:42:20,869
$200,000 fine.

716
00:42:22,373 --> 00:42:23,739
You should have been fired.

717
00:42:23,808 --> 00:42:24,832
Good night, House.

718
00:42:24,909 --> 00:42:26,901
There are bubbles in his glass.

719
00:42:26,978 --> 00:42:28,207
Can this wait until...

720
00:42:28,279 --> 00:42:30,874
My patient. He's
allergic to quinine.

721
00:42:34,152 --> 00:42:36,314
And you got this from bubbles?

722
00:42:36,421 --> 00:42:38,151
<i>His symptoms started
two months ago.</i>

723
00:42:38,589 --> 00:42:40,724
That's also when Brock
started downing gin

724
00:42:40,748 --> 00:42:42,959
and tonics like a Brit
staving off malaria.

725
00:42:44,562 --> 00:42:46,758
Gin was fake,
